<a href="javascript:card_browser(39)">Troop of Uruk-hai</a> x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(42)">Uruk Fighter</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(856)">Uruk Warrior</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(53)">Uruk-hai Raiding Party</a> x2<br>
Ulaire Enquea, Lieutenant of Mordor<br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(25)">Lurtz&#39;s Battle Cry</a> x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(31)">Saruman&#39;s Ambition</a> x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(33)">Saruman&#39;s Power</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(855)">Savagery to Match Their Numbers</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(36)">Spies of Saruman</a> x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(54)">Uruk-hai Rampage</a> x2    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Pre-MoM<br>
Sanctioned Tournament Record: 9-1<br>
<br>
Fellowship:<br>
A deck I made after brainstorming about the weakness of the common Ranger deck which I previously used. It starts Arwen, who is a rather overrated companion in my opinion. She is easy to kill and often will one give her up instead of, say, Legolas Greenleaf. Instead, who&#39;s the superstar everybody likes to draw? Boromir, Lord of Gondor. Combined with Armor, he is almost impossible to kill short of Blade Tips and Hates. This deck starts him and eliminates all traces of Elves in favour of Hobbits. I have laboured long for the meta-game against all the shadow cultures and am satisfied, as Frodo has never been overwhelmed since its creation. It does take some experience and mastering though.<br>
<br>
<b>Against Moria:</b> Six companions is never easy to swarm against. Combine this with the fact that you do not have Elves for those Moria Scouts to spot. The conditions like Goblin Armory and Relics of Moria are still a pain though as you do not have the ability to remove them and they defeat your purpose of choking them. <br>
<br>
Hobbit Stealths should bail out of Site 5 Do not use Stealths before Site 5, and if swarmed, shoot some down and make sure the Backstabbers are assigned to the Hobbits, not to Armor-less Aragorn. This not only prevents Aragorn from dying, but also illusionises to your opponent that your Hobbits are &#39;scared&#39; and in trouble and he will pile them on, and if you were sneaky enough to un-assign the high-vitality minions, he might just stick them on Frodo to Stealth. If possible, do not simply feed Pippin to the Troll. More companions against Moria = more fodder. Just make sure he&#39;s not playing Enquea.<br>
<br>
If Moria is really a big trouble against this deck, substitute the Intuitions for Power According to His Stature. In the next set, Bilbo, Well-Spoken Gentle-Hobbit can provide more tools to combat the Moria twilight-adding, card-drawing, unfair-crap machine.<br>
<br>
<b>Against Nazgul</b>: Men and Hobbits combined have an inherent weakness against Nazgul and so I have solved it with the usage of Merry rare instead of the common version. Note that this deck does not use strength boosters and so, Merry is your only hope to not get Blade Tipped. In the early sites, moderate the twilight carefully as early is when the Ringwraiths are powerful. NEVER play Armor or Blade of Gondor (unless Ranger&#39;s Sword is not out, or it&#39;s &#39;free&#39; at Council Courtyard). For Armor, you will stay below 3 burdens so Nazgul Sword poses no threat. Pale Blade may but you&#39;ll take the chance.<br>
<br>
Nazgul really takes some getting used to. Early ARVs and Stealths can help. Do realise that in 90% of the games against Nazgul. Boromir is going to die. It&#39;s a given. Let him bite the Tips and Breaths if there is really no other hope(NEVER let Aragorn bite even a Tip), and if possible remove them with Athelas, and on next turn, if need be, he&#39;ll bite them again. Make him die in combat, not due to the Tip. It&#39;s okay if you leave the Bridge with Boromir dead. Remember, Boromir with a Breath on him should be killed instead of healthy Pippin and Sam.<br>
<br>
You cannot say the same of Aragorn though. He&#39;s the means by which you win against Nazgul. On the later sites, ARV-Archery provides a very easy double-jump for you to overtake your opponent. Watch out for Relentless Charge. Equip him with Sword quickly and Merry too with a Sword, and in a skirmish, he will be STR 15 Damage +1, which can be enough to take out a Nazgul to avoid the fierce skirmish if it exerted one too many times.<br>
<br>
Nazgul can slow you down horribly but you don&#39;t want him to zoom past you. Slow him down with your shadow, and in the worst case, make sure you reach Site 6 only just after him. Then use your Site 7 with your shadow to stop him. On your turn, ARV-Archery can provide a very good double-jump. On the last site, use every trick in the book. Use Bounder and all the Stealths and Intuitions you saved in your hand. One of Stealth and healthy Bounder are more than enough to see you through Site 9 with just 2 or 3 companions.<br>
<br>
And one more thing, NEVER deploy 6 companions. Hold Pippin or Sam in your hand until Boromir dies.<br>
<br>
Believe me, the Free Peoples is unbeaten against Nazgul. With the advent of Flaming Brands, Boromir and Aragorn will be self-sufficient against Nazgul.<br>
<br>
<b>Against Isengard:</b> You will have to hope you draw that Armor early. This deck uses Isengard so you should know what to expect. Be wary of deploying 5 companions (Savagery), and always watch out if you assign someone without Armor (Lurtz&#39;s Battle Cry). Most Isengard decks are weak now or are simply not played right, so more often than not, your opponent&#39;s folly sees you through this.<br>
<br>
Bear in mind that against Uruks, 1-vitality is the equivalent of 2-vitality. If, say, Boromir and Aragorn both have 2 wounds each, and do not have Armor, discard Athelas to heal Aragorn, so that he will be 2 Isengard skirmishes away from death, instead of both Aragorn and Boromir being 1 skirmish away from death.<br>
<br>
<b>Against Sauron</b>: Choke him early. Very easy to do so. No Strangers, Talent and most importantly, Sting, can limit your opponent to 1 or no minion a turn until Site 5. From then on, it will be dangerous. Never let any of your companions reach exhaustion and limit your wounds and look out for Enquea and promptly limit yourself to 5 companions. ARV can do wonders on the later sites. Try to use Thror&#39;s Map to deny him of Tol Brandir. Isildur&#39;s Bane will allow you to soak up extra archery wounds at Site 9 but make sure he isn&#39;t running Enduring Evil against Frodo. Again, Bounder and Intuition and Stealth pumps can save the day at Site 9.<br>
<br>
Shadow:<br>
I am proud to say that this Isengard half is the best of its kind where I live, and has brought huge success. It is very anti-archery, with 3 Spies and Wilderland. If you don&#39;t get the Spies out, Troop and Raiding Party are solid high-vitality minions which your opponent must exert multiple times to bring them down, which will leave your opponent vulnerable on the next site. Cheap minions like Fighters and Warriors serve the same purpose, and I use them instead of Slayers, Ragers, Guards etc due to their 3-twilight cost, which is very important at Site 5 and later. It isn&#39;t hard to bring 4 of them out together with Spies at the Bridge to spell the end for the opponent.<br>
<br>
Your opponent only needs to let 1 minion in through for you to wreak some SERIOUS havoc. Most people play 5 companions or more and that is perfect for Savagery. Double-Savagery is often more than enough to overwhelm non-Gondor companions. And against Gondor, especially Boromir, this deck utilises the lethal Saruman&#39;s Ambition-Lurtz&#39;s Battle Cry combo. Play Battle Cry for free with Ambition out and discard Ambition if needed to regain your strength. Do so against 3-vitality companions like Boromir, Arwen and Legolas, and save 2 for Aragorn and Gandalf. Companions can be killed very easily, and this often cautions them from moving on to keep up with you on the adventure path.<br>
<br>
Site 5 is where you must do your damage. Try to make sure your Spies are there. If need be, a Troop of Uruk-Hai at Site 4 is very good for exhausting the archers, and if they don&#39;t, he can cause quite a few wounds. Use Spies wisely. Raiding Party and Lurtz do not need it if his archers are exerted, and Troop, almost never.<br>
<br>
Of course, Armor and Gimli&#39;s Helm can shut down the shadow half very quickly. Until you go Beyond the Height of Men, when you see it, quicken your fellowship&#39;s pase. Armor and Helm will make his companions nearly invincible to your Uruks (unless a multiple-Savagery pump overwhelms him) and you must lessen or even abandon your hopes of winning with your shadow half.<br>
<br>
<b>General</b>: Bid 1. Add a burden for Pony and that will be 2. I never like to end up with 3 burdens due to Nazgul Sword, 4 due to Toldea and 5 due to Enquea. If he goes first, fine. Uruks are very good at slowing the opponent down. Almost always make the double-move from Site 1 to 3, remember that the 4 or 5 twilight you give out at Site 3 is often only enough for 1 minion. The exception is of course Nazgul, which in case if you do not double-move, they will either have to stay behind you or overtake you and forego the Ford.<br>
<br>
Try to reach Site 6 before your opponent. From there onwards is where you quicken the pace even more. ARV-Archery kills any deck, and save all the Intuitions and Stealths and Bounder for one last hurrah at Site 9.<br>
<br>
Get the No Strangers and Talents out quickly. Merry is your only strength-booster, and Farmer Maggot + Frodo Rare are there for you to reuse him. Make sure your Uruks kill the opponent&#39;s fellowship before Site 9 or get a big enough force out for him at Site 8 to make him shy away from Site 9. Slopes&#39; reduced cost can bring out a huge group of minions and leave enough for Rampage to make them all fierce but it&#39;s never good to take the chance. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=22053"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=22053" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
